69: /**
70:  * Test routes and mediation rules using mocks.
71:  * <p/>
72:  * A Mock endpoint which provides a literate, fluent API for testing routes using a <a href="http://jmock.org/">JMock
73:  * style</a> API.
74:  * <p/>
75:  * The mock endpoint have two sets of methods
76:  * <ul>
77:  * <li>expectedXXX or expectsXXX - To set pre conditions, before the test is executed</li>
78:  * <li>assertXXX - To assert assertions, after the test has been executed</li>
79:  * </ul>
80:  * Its <b>important</b> to know the difference between the two sets. The former is used to set expectations before the
81:  * test is being started (e.g., before the mock receives messages). The latter is used after the test has been executed,
82:  * to verify the expectations; or other assertions which you can perform after the test has been completed.
83:  * <p/>
84:  * <b>Beware:</b> If you want to expect a mock does not receive any messages, by calling
85:  * {@link #setExpectedMessageCount(int)} with <tt>0</tt>, then take extra care, as <tt>0</tt> matches when the tests
86:  * start, so you need to set an assert period time to let the test run for a while to make sure there are still no
87:  * messages arrived; for that use {@link #setAssertPeriod(long)}. An alternative is to use
88:  * <a href="http://camel.apache.org/notifybuilder.html">NotifyBuilder</a>, and use the notifier to know when Camel is
89:  * done routing some messages, before you call the {@link #assertIsSatisfied()} method on the mocks. This allows you to
90:  * not use a fixed assertion period to speed up testing times.
91:  * <p/>
92:  * <b>Important:</b> If using {@link #expectedMessageCount(int)} and also
93:  * {@link #expectedBodiesReceived(java.util.List)} or {@link #expectedHeaderReceived(String, Object)} then the latter
94:  * overrides the number of expected messages based on the number of values provided in the bodies/headers.
95:  */
